<p><i><b>The Transparent Society</b></i> (1998) is a non-fiction book by the science-fiction author <a href="/wiki/David_Brin" title="David Brin">David Brin</a> in which he forecasts the erosion of <a href="/wiki/Privacy" title="Privacy">privacy</a>, as it is overtaken by low-cost <a href="/wiki/Surveillance" title="Surveillance">surveillance</a>, <a href="/wiki/Communication" title="Communication">communication</a> and <a href="/wiki/Database" title="Database">database</a> technology. The work first appeared as a magazine article by Brin in <i><a href="/wiki/Wired_(magazine)" title="Wired (magazine)">Wired</a></i> in late 1996.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> In 2008, security expert <a href="/wiki/Bruce_Schneier" title="Bruce Schneier">Bruce Schneier</a> called the work a myth,<sup id="cite_ref-Schneier_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Schneier-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> a description Brin rebutted,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> because it ignores wide differences in the relative power of those who access information.<sup id="cite_ref-Schneier_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Schneier-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
